The config map object.

A config map is a key value store of configuration data, scoped to a namespace, that pods reference by name. The values can be short strings or whole files.

It has two sections under the top level. The data section holds string values. The keys are arbitrary, and the values are plain text, you-tee-eff eight strings, with no binary. Almost every config map you will ever write lives here. There is also a binary data section, for base sixty four encoded binary blobs, like a keystore or a small image. That one is much less common.

The crucial thing to understand is that a config map is just data. It has no spec and no status, because there is nothing for a controller to reconcile. The cluster does absolutely nothing with a config map until a pod references it. It simply sits there, holding values, waiting to be consumed.

There is one important limit. A config map, and a secret too, is capped at one mebibyte total. This comes from et-see-dee, because every kubernetes object has to fit inside a single et-see-dee value. So for genuinely large configuration, say a ten megabyte lookup table, you do not use a config map. You put it in object storage, a database, or a sidecar instead.

To put it another way, think of a config map as a small, shared envelope of settings that lives in the cluster. Many pods can point at the same envelope, and you change the settings in one place rather than in every deployment.
